variants: integrate(1/(x**2 + (2)), x)  # (Nothing changes, thus it's an identity)
integrate(0.5 * cos(t)/sin(t)**2, t)  # (with proper substitutions introduced)
integrate(1/(11/4 * (sec(theta)**2)), theta)  # Notice this abstract transformation is still viable by using \(\theta\)
integrate(sum(n/(1 + n**(3)*(u - 1)**2) for n in range(1, 10)), x)
integrate(1/(x + I), x) - integrate(1/(x - I), x)
integrate(1/(2*(x + I)), x) - integrate(1/(2*(x - I)), x)
integrate(1/(1 + k*(sec(t)-1)**2), t)  # Here x = sec(t)
integrate(1/2 * sum(cos(2*pi*k/n) for k in range(n)), x)
integrate(1 / (2 * (u + 1) * (v + 1)), x) where \( u = (e^{ix} - e^{-ix})/(i(e^{ix} + e^{-ix})^2) \) and \( v = e^{ix} + e^{-ix} \)
